# very dry CAPA write-up from a very dry lab
CAPA
 = Common Analysis Platform for Artifacts
 - malware analysis & threat hunting tool
 - makes reverse engineering accesible to noobs
 - identify capabilities present in executables
 - uses a set of rules to describe common behaviors
   to determine what the program is capable of doing


Running the tool is easy
 - cd to the directory where you have the executable
 - capa.exe <executable> (or linux alternative)

capa -h = help
capa <executable> -v = detailed result (or -vv)

Understanding the output is not...

Dissecting CAPA results part 1
 - first block contains basic info:
    - md5, sha1/256
    - analysis (analysis type - eg. static)
    - os
    - arch (architecture)
    - path (path to the executable)

 - ATT&CK Tactic and Technique
    - Defense evasion
    - Discovery
    - Execution
    - Impact
    - Persistence

 - MAEC (Malware Attribute Enumeration and Characterization)
    = specialized language for endoding, communicating complex details about malware
    - MAEC Category
    - MAEC Value
    most common MAEC values are Launcher (triggers actions like malware does)
                                Downloader (downloads or execs other files - complex malware)


Dissecting CAPA results part 2
-> Malware Behavior Catalogue (MBC)
    = catalogue of malware objectives and behaviours
    format: OBJECTIVE::Behavior::Method[Identifier]

    - MBC objective 
        - based on ATT&CK tactics
        - eg. Anti-analysis, CC, Discovery, Exfiltration

    - Micro objectives
        - exhibited micro-behaviors that aren't necesarrily malicious
        - micro-behaviors are typically abused (that's why it's flagged)

    - MBC behavior
        - behaviors / micro-behaviors with or without its methods and identifiers
        - eg. Objective: Anti-behavioral analysis
              Behavior: Lab machine detection
              Identifiers: B0009
              Explanation: The malware checks to see if it is running in a virtual environment. During its system reconnaissance, the malware examines various user and system artifacts.

    - Micro behaviors ("low-level behaviors")
        - eg. Allocate memory, Create process, HTTP communication

    - Methods
        - eg. Argument obfuscation, stack strings, read header, XOR
    
    - example:
        MBC Objective   MBC Behavior
            DATA        Encode Data::Base64 [C0026.001]

        MBC objective = DATA
        MBC behavior = Encode Data
        Method = Base64
        Identifier = C0026.001


Dissecting CAPA results part 3
-> Capability and Namespaces

 - Capability
    - eg. reference anti-VM strings, create process, schedule task
 
 - Namespaces
    - used to group items with the same purpose
    - eg. anti-analysis, collection, compiler, data-manipulation
 - example:
    Top-Level Namespace (TLN): Anti-Analysis
    Namespaces:                anti-vm/vm-detection 
    Rule YAML File:            reference-anti-vm-strings-targeting-virtualbox.yml
    Explanation:               ... contains rules to detect lab machine (VM) environments...


Dissecting CAPA results part 4
-> Capability
 - There was a large table (50+ cols) about capability, TLN, namespace and the rules associated
 - If you're still interested, check their github: https://github.com/MBCProject/capa-rules-1?tab=readme-ov-file#namespace-organization
 - an interesting folder is Nursery (placeholder for rules that are not quite polished yet.)
 - some nursery rules (as of now): capture-webcam-video.yml, power-down-monitor.yml

